
The Earth Compact: A Democratic Framework for Global Governance

Preamble

We, the peoples of Earth, in pursuit of peace, justice, dignity,
and sustainability for all, do establish this Earth Compact.
Acknowledging the interdependence of our global community, the
urgency of planetary crises, and the moral imperative to
safeguard future generations, we hereby commit to a system of
democratic, ethical, and inclusive global governance. This
Compact affirms that legitimate power arises from the will of
the people, is bound by law, and is accountable to the commons
of humanity and Earth.

Article I – Foundations and Principles

1.1 The Earth Compact shall be guided by the core principles of
democracy, sustainability, equity, peace, and transparency.

1.2 Sovereignty is redefined as shared responsibility, where all
peoples participate in shaping the global future.

1.3 All signatory entities commit to uphold and protect
universal human rights, planetary boundaries, and
intergenerational justice.

1.4 No single state, corporation, or individual shall exercise
exclusive authority over global commons.

Article II – Institutions of Global Governance

2.1 A Global Assembly shall be established, composed of
representatives from both national governments and directly
elected citizen delegates.

2.2 An Ethics Council, consisting of impartial elders, legal
scholars, and civic leaders, shall serve as a guardian of the
Compact's moral foundation.

2.3 A Planetary Court shall adjudicate disputes, enforce
compliance, and ensure that global laws reflect the Compact’s
principles.

2.4 An Earth Secretariat shall administer the day-to-day
functions of the Compact and provide open data access to all.

Article XI – Global Ethics Oversight Council (“Ethics Round
Table”)

Section 1. Composition & Tenure
1.1 Comprised of twelve independent members, each serving
staggered four-year terms (maximum one reappointment).
1.2 Members shall reflect global diversity, expertise in ethics,
law, ecology, health, and public reasoning.
1.3 No member shall concurrently hold office in any government
or corporation.

Section 2. Leadership Without a Leader
2.1 Deliberations are guided by rotating facilitators, with no
permanent chair.
2.2 Consensus is preferred; decisions require ≥9/12
supermajority when needed.

Section 3. Mandate & Powers
3.1 Reviews all ethically sensitive global governance proposals.
3.2 Issues binding ethical opinions, which may only be
overridden with public justification.
3.3 Hosts annual global ethics forums for public dialogue.

Section 4. Accountability & Transparency
4.1 Publishes annual impact reports.
4.2 Must respond to any citizen petition with ≥1 million global
signatures.

Article XII – Transition & Voting Mechanisms

Section 1. Founding Constitutional Convention
1.1 500 delegates: 60% elected nationally, 20% civil
society/citizen-appointed, 20% Indigenous and marginalized
communities.
1.2 Elections shall be transparent, verifiable, and globally
accessible.

Section 2. Voting Principles
2.1 All votes shall be secret and equal.
2.2 Global referenda require ≥60% turnout and ≥66% approval to
pass foundational amendments.

Section 3. Citizen Juries
3.1 Randomly selected citizen juries (100–200 people) convene
for deliberation on major constitutional issues.
3.2 Their recommendations are published alongside legislative
debate.

Article XIII – Enforcement & Compliance Mechanisms

Section 1. Global Court of Humanity & Nature
1.1 Composed of 9 judges with overlapping five-year terms.
1.2 Jurisdiction includes: crimes against humanity, ecocide, and
failure to comply with ethical rulings.

Section 2. Enforcement Service
2.1 A professional, non-militarized compliance service shall
operate under court authorization.
2.2 Deploys legal monitors, environmental inspectors, and civic
enforcers.

Section 3. Escalation Protocol
3.1 Violations may be reported by citizens, NGOs, or Compact
institutions.
3.2 Ethics Round Table initiates review; non-compliance triggers
court intervention.

Section 4. No King, No Veto
4.1 All enforcement actions are collective.
4.2 There is no single executive authority or veto-holder.

